00:32:57,515 --> 00:32:59,391
Thanks, Lillian.

463
00:33:05,555 --> 00:33:09,832
"Prosser on Torts." "Civil Procedure."
A little light reading this morning?

464
00:33:09,995 --> 00:33:11,427
Did I invite you to sit down?

465
00:33:11,594 --> 00:33:14,632
No, but you were going to.
Southern hospitality and all.

466
00:33:15,594 --> 00:33:17,983
- Now what?
- Now let's talk about you.

467
00:33:18,153 --> 00:33:20,952
Okay. I like my privacy.
I'm a vegetarian.

468
00:33:21,115 --> 00:33:24,469
I'd appreciate it if you'd take that slab
of ham to the counter with you.

469
00:33:24,634 --> 00:33:27,706
- It gives me the willies.
- I didn't order this slab.

470
00:33:27,874 --> 00:33:31,786
Now I suppose you'll say something cute
to stall your retreat.

471
00:33:31,953 --> 00:33:33,590
Maybe tell me about the big city...

472
00:33:33,752 --> 00:33:36,392
...all the things I'm missing
living in this dinky town...

473
00:33:36,553 --> 00:33:39,624
...and how you'd like to be the one
to take me out of it.

474
00:33:41,832 --> 00:33:44,346
Isn't that why you're going
to law school?

475
00:33:44,512 --> 00:33:46,786
You want to get out
of this dinky little town.

476
00:33:47,151 --> 00:33:51,303
I'm not going yet. And I plan to practice
in Grady when I'm through.

477
00:33:52,152 --> 00:33:54,712
Yeah, it looks like a hotbed
of legal activity.

478
00:33:54,871 --> 00:33:58,545
Well, malpractice for visiting young
surgeons seems promising.

479
00:33:58,951 --> 00:34:00,543
Who's the green apple, Vialula?

480
00:34:01,271 --> 00:34:03,625
- Henry, this is Ben Stone.
- Hey.

481
00:34:03,790 --> 00:34:06,100
Oh, yeah, the new croaker.

482
00:34:06,270 --> 00:34:07,702
Hank Gordon.

483
00:34:07,869 --> 00:34:09,144
You're in my chair.

484
00:34:10,870 --> 00:34:12,825
- Boyfriend?
- "Friend" friend.

485
00:34:22,709 --> 00:34:25,303
- Need any life insurance?
- What?

486
00:34:25,469 --> 00:34:28,586
You should be vested
in a term life program.

487
00:34:28,749 --> 00:34:31,022
Probably a quarter of a mil to start.

488
00:34:31,308 --> 00:34:33,775
Come by my office.
We could run a "what if."

489
00:34:34,068 --> 00:34:35,865
Or are you too chicken?

490
00:34:38,946 --> 00:34:41,781
I read somewhere doctors have
the highest suicide rate...

491
00:34:41,947 --> 00:34:43,857
...in any profession except dentistry.

492
00:34:44,026 --> 00:34:47,575
- Is that true?
- I won't underwrite dentists. Nope.

493
00:34:47,746 --> 00:34:50,738
Never trust a man who'll put his hand
in your mouth.

494
00:34:51,066 --> 00:34:54,217
Well, I'd love to stay and hear
where this conversation's headed...

495
00:34:54,385 --> 00:34:56,581
...but if you all will excuse me.

496
00:34:57,704 --> 00:35:00,778
There's something else
I wanted to ask you.

497
00:35:01,344 --> 00:35:05,896
Do doctors know more about sex
than normal people?

498
00:35:08,704 --> 00:35:11,265
I need some ketchup.

499
00:35:11,864 --> 00:35:14,298
I have a fair knowledge
of animal husbandry.

500
00:35:14,464 --> 00:35:16,615
It's all pretty much the same thing.

501
00:35:16,943 --> 00:35:18,297
- Bye, doc.
- Bye.

502
00:35:18,464 --> 00:35:20,931
Women trouble, Ben Stone?

503
00:35:21,584 --> 00:35:23,381
Squat here.

504
00:35:26,143 --> 00:35:29,215
- Regard the Grady squash.
- Looks like a yellow zucchini.

505
00:35:29,382 --> 00:35:34,059
Nope. See, up until 1933, you had your
Grady, you had your zucchini.

506
00:35:34,223 --> 00:35:35,974
They're going at it, gourd to gourd.

507
00:35:36,143 --> 00:35:39,531
Freak tornado accident wiped out
a whole shipment of Gradys...

508
00:35:39,702 --> 00:35:44,616
...bound for, I believe, agricultural
stardom at the Chicago World's Fair.

509
00:35:44,782 --> 00:35:46,897
The zucchini took there.
Never relented.

510
00:35:47,182 --> 00:35:51,014
If it had gone the other way, no telling
where this town would be today.

511
00:35:51,780 --> 00:35:53,418
What are you talking about?

512
00:35:54,101 --> 00:35:56,899
Timing. Same thing with women.

513
00:35:57,060 --> 00:35:59,973
And with Southern women,
they require substantial commitment.

514
00:36:00,140 --> 00:36:02,699
You might have to stay here
for six months, maybe more.

515
00:36:02,860 --> 00:36:06,409
- Are you a betting man, Nick?
- I have been known on occasion.

516
00:36:07,380 --> 00:36:09,371
- Take me about a week.
- Now, wait a minute.

517
00:36:09,540 --> 00:36:13,930
- You mean Vialula in the center pocket?
- Ten bucks.

518
00:36:16,098 --> 00:36:18,374
Okay, you got it.

519
00:36:19,499 --> 00:36:21,853
Feels like I'm fleecing you, Ben Stone.

520
00:36:24,618 --> 00:36:26,369
Easy.

521
00:36:29,178 --> 00:36:31,328
Hello, Nurse Packer.

522
00:36:33,978 --> 00:36:35,490
All right.

523
00:36:35,657 --> 00:36:38,171
Okay, let's get something straight
right now.

524
00:36:38,337 --> 00:36:42,933
I got eight years of higher education, one
year of internship, one year of residency.

525
00:36:43,097 --> 00:36:44,529
I'm $ 70,000 in debt.

526
00:36:44,697 --> 00:36:47,086
Now I'm waylaid in this heehaw hell...

527
00:36:47,257 --> 00:36:50,646
...and you insist on clocking me in
and out like I'm a factory worker.

528
00:36:50,816 --> 00:36:54,491
Well, no! N-O, no!
This is where I draw the line.

529
00:36:55,697 --> 00:36:58,654
I believe you have a visitor, doctor.

530
00:37:01,936 --> 00:37:06,406
Doc, my foot feels so good,
I brought you this pig.

531
00:37:09,694 --> 00:37:11,366
Okay.

532
00:37:11,535 --> 00:37:14,413
I can't abide being in no man's debt.

533
00:37:14,576 --> 00:37:16,849
This pig's all I got to give.

534
00:37:18,734 --> 00:37:21,487
I'm already paid, more or less,
by the hospital.

535
00:37:21,655 --> 00:37:25,363
- I really can't accept your pig.
- It's a done deal.

536
00:37:26,374 --> 00:37:28,489
She's your pig now.

537
00:37:29,613 --> 00:37:31,729
God bless you both.

538
00:37:37,453 --> 00:37:40,250
Keep your animal outside.
This is a hospital.

539
00:37:53,490 --> 00:37:55,721
- Nice pig there, doc.
- Thank you.

540
00:37:55,892 --> 00:37:58,608
- Lovely pig.
- Thank you very much. Appreciate it.

541
00:37:58,770 --> 00:38:02,001
- Nice pig, doc!
- Thank you.

542
00:38:02,170 --> 00:38:05,003
Thank you all very much.

543
00:38:11,010 --> 00:38:16,446
Ben Stone. Say, I think I just took away
your last reason to go to California.

544
00:38:16,608 --> 00:38:19,363
Norrisville Drum and Bugle Corps.

545
00:38:19,529 --> 00:38:21,644
They played last four years
in the Rose Parade.

546
00:38:21,808 --> 00:38:25,164
I got them under exclusive contract
to the Grady Squash Festival.

547
00:38:25,328 --> 00:38:26,727
I'm not staying.

548
00:38:27,129 --> 00:38:28,527
Sure, you aren't.

549
00:38:28,688 --> 00:38:31,679
Oh, by the way, dinner at my house
tomorrow night, 6:00.

550
00:38:31,887 --> 00:38:33,367
- Dinner?
- Didn't I tell you?

551
00:38:33,528 --> 00:38:34,802
You're guest of honor.

552
00:38:35,727 --> 00:38:39,117
Shoot a monkey. If my head wasn't
attached, I'd need wood screws.

553
00:38:39,288 --> 00:38:40,800
- Nice pig, doc.
- Thanks.

554
00:38:40,967 --> 00:38:43,084
Can I bring a date?

555
00:38:43,246 --> 00:38:45,806
Well, I don't know. Can you?

556
00:38:47,926 --> 00:38:51,635
This is Ben Stone you're talking to.
Come on, pig.

557
00:38:53,086 --> 00:38:55,280
Fine pig, doc.

558
00:38:59,964 --> 00:39:01,081
Melvin.

559
00:39:01,686 --> 00:39:04,836
Melvin. Melvin.

560
00:39:05,044 --> 00:39:08,435
Hey, doc. We're just rehearsing
for the pageant.

561
00:39:08,605 --> 00:39:11,834
We doing a pollination rap song.

562
00:39:14,844 --> 00:39:16,118
Melvin, listen.

563
00:39:16,285 --> 00:39:20,561
I don't have the money
for the oil-gepumpkin-hausen thing.

564
00:39:22,683 --> 00:39:26,517
I mean, when I say I haven't got
the money, that's not entirely true.

565
00:39:26,683 --> 00:39:28,515
I have the money.
I'm good for the money.

566
00:39:28,683 --> 00:39:31,595
It's just a matter of accessing
the money in a period of time.

567
00:39:31,763 --> 00:39:34,401
Can we work something out, please?

568
00:39:34,562 --> 00:39:37,475
This car has got to be ready
by the time I leave.

569
00:39:40,722 --> 00:39:43,759
- That your pig?
- Yeah.

570
00:39:51,401 --> 00:39:55,314
You want to trade? Pig for the part?

571
00:39:56,080 --> 00:39:58,152
If you can part with the pig.

572
00:40:01,121 --> 00:40:02,110
Good.

573
00:40:07,200 --> 00:40:09,634
- Hi.
- Hi.

574
00:40:14,560 --> 00:40:17,711
- You just pick those?
- Yes, ma'am.

575
00:40:18,519 --> 00:40:21,795
They're protected by law.
State flowers.

576
00:40:24,279 --> 00:40:25,951
Figures.

577
00:40:26,360 --> 00:40:30,476
I'm already serving time for the fence.
May as well take my chances, right?

578
00:40:30,638 --> 00:40:34,870
Mama. Mama, who is it?
Who are you?

579
00:40:38,157 --> 00:40:39,876
I'm Ben.

580
00:40:41,117 --> 00:40:43,551
Emma, take these inside
and put them in some water.

581
00:40:43,718 --> 00:40:46,106
You're not supposed to pick these.

582
00:40:46,436 --> 00:40:48,268
Use the plastic pitcher.

583
00:40:50,837 --> 00:40:52,747
Yeah, she's mine.

584
00:40:52,915 --> 00:40:55,590
She's 4. You wanna retreat now or...?

585
00:40:55,756 --> 00:40:57,314
No, no, no.

586
00:40:57,475 --> 00:41:00,149
No. Actually, I just came by...

587
00:41:00,315 --> 00:41:03,671
...because I need a date for dinner
tomorrow night.

588
00:41:03,835 --> 00:41:06,712
- Nick Nicholson's?
- Yeah. How'd you know?

589
00:41:07,035 --> 00:41:10,344
Can't poop in this town without
everyone knowing what color it is.

590
00:41:16,995 --> 00:41:20,270
I was fixing to have a cocktail.

591
00:41:20,475 --> 00:41:22,226
Are you in a hurry?

592
00:41:24,713 --> 00:41:26,704
Oh, man, that's tart.

593
00:41:26,874 --> 00:41:30,832
It's called a "Slow Comfortable Screw
Up Against a Wall," with a twist.

594
00:41:30,994 --> 00:41:33,905
- Is that a Grady specialty?
- No.

595
00:41:34,073 --> 00:41:36,427
- New York City.
- New York?

596
00:41:36,592 --> 00:41:39,743
Yeah. I worked at one of those
weirdo theme bars on the West Side.

597
00:41:39,911 --> 00:41:42,506
Wayne and I went to college
in New York.

598
00:41:43,192 --> 00:41:44,910
Then he dropped out.

599
00:41:45,072 --> 00:41:48,906
I got pregnant.
He couldn't get work, so I bartended.

600
00:41:49,071 --> 00:41:51,426
I managed to finish school, though.

601
00:41:51,590 --> 00:41:54,059
- Wayne isn't still...?
- Wayne...

602
00:41:54,232 --> 00:41:57,223
...is a professional dancer.

603
00:41:57,391 --> 00:41:59,345
One of those
exotic Chippendale things.

604
00:41:59,510 --> 00:42:02,820
He's in Boston, Miami...
I can't keep track.

605
00:42:03,231 --> 00:42:05,461
He left me after Emma was born.

606
00:42:05,631 --> 00:42:08,541
I divorced him
and came running back here.

607
00:42:08,950 --> 00:42:13,943
Wayne has this extremely high opinion
of his legs.

608
00:42:14,109 --> 00:42:16,703
You know, I just can't picture you
in the big city.

609
00:42:16,869 --> 00:42:18,620
New York.

610
00:42:18,949 --> 00:42:20,428
It's like me...

611
00:42:20,590 --> 00:42:22,897
- In Grady?
- Yeah.

612
00:42:23,909 --> 00:42:26,423
Well, peel an onion,
there's lots of layers.

613
00:42:28,389 --> 00:42:29,868
What layer is Hank on?

614
00:42:31,108 --> 00:42:33,986
Henry Gordon's sweet on me.

615
00:42:34,507 --> 00:42:36,339
And he's pretty decent and solid...

616
00:42:36,508 --> 00:42:39,864
...once you get past the "Insurance
Rebel Without a Clause" routine.

617
00:42:40,507 --> 00:42:42,622
Decent and solid.

618
00:42:43,148 --> 00:42:44,421
Very romantic.

619
00:42:47,227 --> 00:42:52,061
I can see you coming from half a mile
away, Dr. Stone.

620
00:42:52,226 --> 00:42:54,377
You and your slick city ways.

621
00:42:54,547 --> 00:42:56,264
I suspect your version of romance...

622
00:42:56,424 --> 00:42:59,338
...is whatever will separate me
from my panties.

623
00:43:00,865 --> 00:43:04,302
Look, all I'm talking about is dinner.

624
00:43:04,464 --> 00:43:07,105
In public. Wear a dress.

625
00:43:07,266 --> 00:43:09,414
Panties are optional.

626
00:43:10,784 --> 00:43:14,664
Well, I never have had dinner
at the mayor's house.

627
00:43:14,825 --> 00:43:16,861
Oh, boy.

628
00:43:17,463 --> 00:43:20,615
And after all,
how could I possibly refuse the man...

629
00:43:20,784 --> 00:43:22,933
...who saved Jasmine
from the butcher?

630
00:43:24,342 --> 00:43:27,654
- What are you talking about?
- Tidwell's pig.

631
00:43:27,822 --> 00:43:29,939
He was about to sell her
for pork chops...

632
00:43:30,103 --> 00:43:32,981
...if you hadn't fixed his foot,
made him feel guilty.

633
00:43:33,143 --> 00:43:36,499
Emma loves pigs.
You keeping her over at your house?

634
00:43:43,183 --> 00:43:44,855
Lane, where's Melvin?

635
00:43:45,182 --> 00:43:48,459
Where's Melvin? I want my pig back.

636
00:43:50,700 --> 00:43:53,454
Did you say he went to church?
At this hour?

637
00:43:55,861 --> 00:44:00,173
Are you allowed to come out here?
I can't understand what you're saying.

638
00:44:00,340 --> 00:44:03,696
Melvin's gone to church.
He's gone to Tylerville.

639
00:44:03,861 --> 00:44:06,249
The pig got took to the butcher.

640
00:44:07,021 --> 00:44:09,215
Melvin took my pig to the butcher.

641
00:44:09,980 --> 00:44:11,537
What?

642
00:44:19,419 --> 00:44:21,774
Mr. Crawford, where's my pig?

643
00:44:21,938 --> 00:44:24,533
You know, Jasmine, my pig.
Is she still alive?

644
00:44:24,699 --> 00:44:27,166
- Yes. She's in back.
- Thank God. Thank God.

645
00:44:27,338 --> 00:44:29,568
- I want her back.
- Doc...

646
00:44:29,738 --> 00:44:32,251
I know what you're going to say.
Do you take plastic?

647
00:44:32,417 --> 00:44:35,012
Not unless it's wrapped around
a stack of cash.

648
00:44:35,177 --> 00:44:36,897
Maybe we can work it out in trade.

649
00:44:37,057 --> 00:44:40,253
I don't know. I ain't been sick
in three years, doc.

650
00:44:41,016 --> 00:44:43,212
I got an idea.

651
00:44:50,736 --> 00:44:55,173
Where'd you learn to carve like that?
You're pretty darn good with a knife.

652
00:45:00,216 --> 00:45:02,171
- Hey, Maddie. Hey, Emma.
- Hi, doc.

653
00:45:02,335 --> 00:45:04,930
You guys are pig-sitting
for me tonight?

654
00:45:05,096 --> 00:45:06,528
Hey, Jasmine.

655
00:45:06,695 --> 00:45:08,254
- Who are you?
- Don't tease me.

656
00:45:08,415 --> 00:45:10,451
I'm serious.
You look like Lou, but prettier.

657
00:45:10,614 --> 00:45:14,049
I'm warning you, Stone, I could
probably whoop you in a fistfight.

658
00:45:14,214 --> 00:45:17,252
- Be a good girl.
- Bye.

659
00:45:17,415 --> 00:45:19,052
- Be a good girl.
- We'll be late.

660
00:45:19,213 --> 00:45:23,002
Not too much TV for her.
She's a real pig about that.

661
00:45:26,893 --> 00:45:31,841
Hi. Come on in. Welcome.
You look fantastic.

662
00:45:32,013 --> 00:45:33,684
- And you look handsome too.
- Thanks.

663
00:45:33,852 --> 00:45:36,810
Daddy's in the back yard tending
the firestorm in the barbecue.

664
00:45:36,972 --> 00:45:41,204
- So you're Nick's daughter.
- Gosh, I hope so, I'm in his will.

665
00:45:41,372 --> 00:45:43,761
Hey, y'all, look who's here.

666
00:45:44,412 --> 00:45:46,483
Hello, Lou. Hello, Stone.

667
00:45:46,652 --> 00:45:48,403
Check Hollywood for knives.

668
00:45:48,572 --> 00:45:53,007
I don't want him operating on me later
in case I sneeze or something.

669
00:45:54,050 --> 00:45:56,166
Isn't this gonna be fun?

670
00:45:57,931 --> 00:46:01,970
- Oh, no, thank you, I'm a vegetarian.
- I know, dear, but I'm still hopeful.

671
00:46:02,130 --> 00:46:04,518
So am I. Vegetarian.

672
00:46:04,689 --> 00:46:07,285
- Since when?
- Then have some of this squash, Ben.

673
00:46:07,449 --> 00:46:08,963
Flesh of the earth. Don't be shy.

674
00:46:09,130 --> 00:46:12,202
I'm not sure I trust a man
who doesn't eat meat.

675
00:46:12,369 --> 00:46:15,965
Don't be so provincial.
Where's your sense of adventure?

676
00:46:16,129 --> 00:46:20,599
I'd probably give vegetarians a better rate
for life insurance than a smoker, though.

677
00:46:20,768 --> 00:46:23,408
On account of that
lower cholesterol factor.

678
00:46:23,568 --> 00:46:27,720
Daddy, please, new subject.
We wanna hear all about California.

679
00:46:27,888 --> 00:46:30,640
I heard the women out there
have their chests enlarged...

680
00:46:30,806 --> 00:46:33,880
...their thighs vacuumed
and barf on purpose.

681
00:46:34,048 --> 00:46:36,083
Not while people are eating.

682
00:46:36,248 --> 00:46:39,478
Yeah, tell us about
real doctoring, Stone.

683
00:46:39,646 --> 00:46:42,241
You know, big-city medicine.

684
00:46:42,407 --> 00:46:45,956
So much has changed in the 40 years
since you went to medical school...

685
00:46:46,126 --> 00:46:47,719
...I wouldn't know where to start.

686
00:46:49,127 --> 00:46:51,117
- Smart-ass.
- Got you good.

687
00:46:51,606 --> 00:46:54,358
- More squash, Ben?
- No. I mean, no, thank you.

688
00:46:55,125 --> 00:47:00,120
Out of the cradle
Endlessly rocking

689
00:47:00,286 --> 00:47:03,596
Out of the mockingbird's throat

690
00:47:03,764 --> 00:47:06,438
The musical shuttle

691
00:47:06,604 --> 00:47:08,596
Out of the ninth month

692
00:47:08,765 --> 00:47:11,563
- Is this one of the long ones?
- No.

693
00:47:13,164 --> 00:47:14,882
Long ones?

694
00:47:15,525 --> 00:47:17,799
Doc Hogue does the complete
Walt Whitman...

695
00:47:17,964 --> 00:47:20,273
...if you don't monitor his drinking.

696
00:47:20,444 --> 00:47:23,880
Down from the shower'd halo

697
00:47:24,043 --> 00:47:27,956
Up from the mystical play of shadows

698
00:47:30,763 --> 00:47:33,993
Man, I haven't seen
this many stars in a long time.

699
00:47:34,444 --> 00:47:37,958
I used to get so bored in this town,
I'd try to count them.

700
00:47:38,284 --> 00:47:40,194
I could've gone to med school.

